[5] Northwest Territories (Tlicho region)
Date: Fri 13 Dec 2019
Source: CBC [edited]
https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/whooping-cough-pertussis-nwt-confirmed-1.5396024


There are 8 confirmed cases of whooping cough in the N.W.T.'s Tlicho region, warns the health department in a news release Friday [13 Dec 2019]. The department says that as of Friday [13 Dec 2019], the 8 lab-confirmed cases are "being controlled," and there haven't been hospitalizations. It also says the cases are "localized" but did not list the affected community or communities. "All confirmed cases have been isolated and treated," states the news release.

Whooping cough is preventable with a vaccine, according to the department. Residents can get the free vaccine from their healthcare provider.

In 2015, there were 21 confirmed cases of whooping cough in N.W.T., in the Tlicho region, Hay River, Yellowknife, and the Beaufort Delta. At the time, the office of the chief public health officer said the majority of these cases were linked to travel outside the N.W.T.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Northwest Territories (NWT) (2019, estimated population 44 826) is a federal territory of Canada bordered by the territories of Nunavut to the east and Yukon to the west, and by the provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan to the south; Yellowknife is the territorial capital (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northwest_Territories). Aboriginal peoples are in the majority in NWT. The Tlicho region, where there are 8 confirmed cases of whooping cough, may refer to the place where the Tlicho people live, between Great Slave and Great Bear Lakes in the NWT (https://www.google.com/maps/place/Great+Slave+Lake). - Mod.ML]
